This paper is primarily focused on deep neural networks and their training process, which falls under the category of machine learning (cs.LG). The paper specifically addresses the lottery ticket hypothesis in the context of adversarial training, which involves manipulating input data to test the robustness of a model, suggesting a connection to computer vision (cs.CV). Additionally, the paper proposes a method for finding sub-networks that converge faster during training, which could be considered an optimization problem falling under artificial intelligence (cs.AI) or neural networks (cs.NE). Finally, the paper discusses the implications of their findings for improving the robustness of models against attacks, which could be considered a security issue (cs.CR).
